node.text:
How far can your dreams take you? Further than you ever imagined. ‚ú®‚Å£
‚Å£
Just ask Anthony Ramos (@anthonyramosofficial) and Leslie Grace (@lesliegrace), stars of the upcoming movie musical ‚ÄúIn the Heights‚Äù (@intheheightsmovie). As two of the film‚Äôs central characters, they can relate in more ways than one to the struggles, triumphs and, of course, dreams that their characters have for themselves. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI always dreamt of going off into the world and finding other places that felt like home. And that‚Äôs what our movie is about,‚Äù says Leslie. ‚ÄúYou see so many of our characters follow their dreams and think that they‚Äôre in other places, or they find them in the very place that made them up. I know for Anthony and I, a lot of our dreams have been made up and inspired by our love of music.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Speaking of music, the film‚Äôs melodies highlight and celebrate the authentic stories within the Latinx community ‚Äî stories of hardship, tradition and dreams becoming fulfilled.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúDon‚Äôt let anyone stop you from going after your dreams wholeheartedly,‚Äù says Anthony. ‚ÄúYou can do anything you set your mind to if you work hard enough and dream big enough.‚Äù üíôüíô‚Å£
‚Å£
#TakeABreak with these dreamers in a musical extravaganza as they share never-before-heard versions of two original songs from the movie. üé∂üíïüéºüí´‚Å£

node.title: Dreaming to the Highest Heightsüéµ with @anthonyramosofficial & @lesliegrace

node.text:
We asked 9-year-old Alan Kim (@official.alankim) what his dream movie would be to write, produce and star in‚Ä¶ and this is the trailer. üé¨

You may know him as the breakout star of ‚ÄúMinari‚Äù (@minarimovie), but Hollywood newcomer Alan Kim is just getting started taking the film world by storm. In this exclusive trailer to his latest make-believe cinematic masterpiece he‚Äôs calling ‚ÄúThe Search,‚Äù Alan sets off on an epic journey to rescue his best friend (and adorable puppy) Cream who‚Äôs been stolen by an evil magician.

‚ÄúCream‚Äôs dream finally came true: him being a star,‚Äù says Alan of his original screenplay.

But the dream doesn‚Äôt end there. While we get to enjoy a sneak peek at the movie of Alan‚Äôs imagination, he‚Äôll be experiencing another dream fulfilled as he attends his first #Oscars, where ‚ÄúMinari‚Äù is nominated for six @theacademy awards. Tune in tonight on @abcnetwork.

Now shhh! The trailer is starting! ü§´üçø

node.title: Alan Kim‚Äôs Dream Movie: The Trailer

‚ÄúGetting involved in environmental action isn‚Äôt about being perfect, it‚Äôs about just doing what you can.‚Äù ‚ÄîEnvironmental communicator Summer Dean (@climatediva)

Today on IGTV, listen to Summer, along with environmental and Indigenous rights defender Helena Gualinga (@helenagualinga) and @kidsagainstpalstic co-founders Amy and Ella Meek, discuss the most urgent environmental issues facing the planet today. They also share some everyday things you can do to make a difference.

Despite all the challenges facing the planet, these activists remain hopeful. ‚ÄúIt gives me a lot of comfort knowing that all of the solutions we need are in nature,‚Äù says Summer. ‚ÄúWe just need to come together and figure out how to make that happen.‚Äù #EarthDay üåç

node.text:
Comedic R&B. Dream soul. New jack swing. Quiet storm. And a little bit of chaos.

That‚Äôs how Tima Diakite (@timalikesmusic) describes the music she produces about relatable, funny everyday moments.

‚ÄúI love that feeling of waking up to R&B radio Sunday morning knowing you had to clean or waking up to gospel music. Whenever I‚Äôm creating music, I try to recapture that vibe.

How did I feel at my aunt‚Äôs wedding? How did I feel at my graduation cookout? I try to capture that because the Black experience, it‚Äôs like no other. I‚Äôm telling you, it‚Äôs a vibe.‚Äù

This Black History Month, we continue to #ShareBlackStories and celebrate Black joy in all its glory. üñ§

node.text:
Japanese artist and designer Verdy (@verdy) always loved drawing characters. After years of doodling in notebooks, the iconic ‚ÄúVick‚Äù came to life. ‚úçüìí‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI feel like we‚Äôve grown up together over many years,‚Äù says Verdy. ‚ÄúHaving the same personality as myself, he is always positive, takes on new challenges and is also pretty easygoing.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
The amount of time Verdy‚Äôs spent at home alone with his drawings last year gave him time to think about what‚Äôs important. ‚ÄúUp until now I thought I wanted to become an artist from Japan that gets to go out into the world. But now I want to be an artist that represents Asia.‚Äù üåè‚ú®‚Å£
‚Å£
If you‚Äôre needing some new year inspiration, #TakeABreak with Verdy (and his sidekick Vick) to see his work and passion in full force.

For artist Sipho Mabona (@siphomabona) beauty lies in the abstract. ‚ÄúFragments of crease patterns, which originally served as blueprints for origami sculptures, have become metaphors of what might have been,‚Äù he explains.‚Å£
‚Å£
Sipho‚Äôs process uses natural dyes and cotton fabric, and he finds that solitary moments of creation in his studio are some of the best ways to find calm and focus throughout his days.

‚ÄúI like to dance to fast music, with a fast rope.‚Äù ‚Äî KO-YA (@ko_ya.reg) ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The three-time double Dutch world champion and leader of the REGSTYLE crew describes the frenetic speed and synchronized movements of his performances as a totally immersive experience. ‚ÄúI feel the space inside the rope with all five senses,‚Äù says KO-YA, who loves to practice his skills ‚Äî which can be over 160 beats per minute ‚Äî on the streets. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
‚ÄúOne of the elements that attracts me to double Dutch is the fact that I can mix with many cultures. I like street culture, hip-hop, dance and sports, and I feel like double Dutch has a lot of these elements.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Camaraderie is also a big part of KO-YA‚Äôs love for double Dutch. ‚ÄúIt allows me to learn about the importance of having a team, since I perform with my friends. I dream of making the world full of smiles and of connecting with lots of people.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Video by @ko_ya.reg

node.text:
How far can your dreams take you? Further than you ever imagined. ‚ú®‚Å£
‚Å£
Just ask Anthony Ramos (@anthonyramosofficial) and Leslie Grace (@lesliegrace), stars of the upcoming movie musical ‚ÄúIn the Heights‚Äù (@intheheightsmovie). As two of the film‚Äôs central characters, they can relate in more ways than one to the struggles, triumphs and, of course, dreams that their characters have for themselves. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI always dreamt of going off into the world and finding other places that felt like home. And that‚Äôs what our movie is about,‚Äù says Leslie. ‚ÄúYou see so many of our characters follow their dreams and think that they‚Äôre in other places, or they find them in the very place that made them up. I know for Anthony and I, a lot of our dreams have been made up and inspired by our love of music.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Speaking of music, the film‚Äôs melodies highlight and celebrate the authentic stories within the Latinx community ‚Äî stories of hardship, tradition and dreams becoming fulfilled.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúDon‚Äôt let anyone stop you from going after your dreams wholeheartedly,‚Äù says Anthony. ‚ÄúYou can do anything you set your mind to if you work hard enough and dream big enough.‚Äù üíôüíô‚Å£
‚Å£
#TakeABreak with these dreamers in a musical extravaganza as they share never-before-heard versions of two original songs from the movie. üé∂üíïüéºüí´‚Å£

node.text:
Kijana ‚ÄúKiko‚Äù Robinson (@kik0xx) first dreamed about starting her own cosmetics line when she graduated high school. ‚ÄúI was just getting serious into makeup, and at that time there wasn‚Äôt that much Black-girl-friendly makeup,‚Äù says the 23-year-old entrepreneur. ‚ÄúSo the thought came to my mind that I should start my own cosmetic line that would be accessible to everyone.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Fast forward three years and Kiko‚Äôs dream became her reality when her social media followers‚Äô love for her personal makeup looks motivated her to launch her e-commerce business Kik0xxstensions (@kik0xxstensions). ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Kiko is known for her colorful handmade, cruelty-free eyelash extensions and eyeliner with an aesthetic that she says ‚Äúseeks to celebrate being true to yourself and spreading positive vibes.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
‚ÄúThe message I'd like to send through my work is to be carefree, strong and do what makes you happy,‚Äù says Kiko. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs important to support Black businesses because we‚Äôre able to create more visibility, representation and jobs for the Black community.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Photos by @kik0xx

node.text:
‚ÄúThe possibilities are infinite,‚Äù says creative director and 3D artist Antoni Tudisco (@antonitudisco).‚Å£
‚Å£
The Filipino-Italian‚Äôs constantly evolving digital imagery seamlessly blends surrealism and reality and seemingly knows no boundaries. ‚ÄúI hope for my audience to feel confused with what‚Äôs real and what‚Äôs digital. I want them to be surprised with what they see,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúI always present them with something new and that they‚Äôve never seen before or ever expected to see. Something unforgettable.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Antoni‚Äôs collaboration with fashion designer Ding Yun Zhang (@dingyun_zhang) is a marriage made in utopia: a series of stills and videos that blend Antoni‚Äôs hybrid figures wearing exaggerated renderings of Ding‚Äôs futuristic oversized puffer jackets within fantastic landscapes.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI have always been fashion-oriented since I could remember. And now I‚Äôm trying to create my own 3D fashion world. I would love to bring the 3D textures and looks I digitally create into tactile existence one day,‚Äù says Antoni.‚Å£
‚Å£
As always with Antoni the future is now ‚Äî he recently started the clothing brand @tudisco.studio.‚Å£
‚Å£
Illustrations by @antonitudisco

node.text:
‚ÄúMusic is the only way I can express myself, totally and truly,‚Äù says 20-year-old Paravi Das (@pxrxvi). ‚ÄúI like to say there‚Äôs a way to find passion in any song, but it becomes a different sort of magic when you can make a song your own,‚Äù explains the singer-songwriter who has recently seen her cover versions go viral and also makes original music.

‚ÄúLike many children of immigrants, as proud as I am of my culture and heritage, I don‚Äôt feel I completely belong to India, and I don‚Äôt feel I completely belong to America. I find it easier to feel that sense of grounding when I choose to honor both sides of my being, rather than pretend the other doesn‚Äôt exist.

The API community is so often overlooked, especially when it comes to entertainment and music. The things I loved most in life ‚Äî singing, art, acting, performing ‚Äî never loved me back, because I never saw someone at the top of these industries that looked like me.
Acknowledging and celebrating unrecognized voices can allow us to make beautiful things. There‚Äôs so much more to us ‚Äî so much more beauty, talent, love, culture and authenticity. Just take a second for a closer look.‚Äù

This month, we‚Äôre celebrating #APIHeritageMonth by sharing creative voices from the community. #RethinkOurInfluence

Reel and music by @pxrxvi

node.text:
Ever wonder how prom started? üï∫üéäüé∂
Comedian Lonnie Marts IIV (@lonnieiiv) breaks down the origin story. üòÇüòÇ

‚ÄúMy prom experience was pretty standard. I was a weirdo in a Hawaiian shirt running around, hyping everybody up. And I think I did a really good job ‚Äî like, I would want to hang out with me at prom again,‚Äù says Lonnie, who describes his comedy as quirky, optimistic and thoughtful.

‚ÄúI‚Äôm an optimist so I look at a lot of things like, ‚ÄòHow can we have the most fun with this? How can we make this something that everyone will enjoy and want to be a part of?‚Äô I do that with my content, my audience and my community too ‚Äî I love involving people and bringing everybody together to just have a great time.‚Äù

Putting his humor aside, Lonnie recognizes that many proms this year may still look or feel different from proms of years past, but he has advice on keeping a positive outlook. ‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre missing out on something, it‚Äôs OK to be sad about it. Cry about it ‚Äî but then pick your head up, get with some good people who know how to be imaginative and get excited about doing what you can do and make it the best darn time you‚Äôve ever had.‚Äù üíõ‚ù§Ô∏è

Reel by @lonnieiiv featuring @jenningsbrower

‚ÄúI think one of the most beautiful things that we can give to one another is our vulnerability.‚Äù üíï

Introducing Vancouver, Canada-based singer/songwriter Jessia (@jessiamusic) and her latest hit ‚ÄúI‚Äôm Not Pretty,‚Äù a song that started as a form of personal therapy for the musician and has since become a far-reaching anthem for self-acceptance and body positivity.
üé∂ üíñ üé∂

‚ÄúI feel like the lyrics have helped me,‚Äù says Jessia. ‚ÄúI am the most confident I‚Äôve ever been in my body and I love the person that I look at in the mirror every morning. I don't think I ever felt that way before ‚ÄòI‚Äôm Not Pretty.‚Äô I also feel like I‚Äôm just the messenger of this song, and this song is so much bigger than just me as an artist.‚Äù

In theme with #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth, the message of Jessia‚Äôs song aims to inspire people to let go of the need for validation from others and to love themselves fully and freely.

‚ÄúAin‚Äôt nobody got time for social comparisons,‚Äù says Jessia. ‚ÄúJust do you and just rock it. Do exactly what you want to do and honestly it‚Äôs going to work out so much better than trying to be someone else. Building that relationship with yourself where you‚Äôre 100% comfortable with who you are is a really, really beautiful thing.‚Äù

For more resources from mental health experts and creators, check out our Guide on the ways to combat social comparison. And to hear more from Jessia, check out our story now! ‚ú®‚ú®

Reel by @jessiamusic
Music by @jessiamusic

node.text:
‚ÄúMy freestyle riding represents who I am. It is an extension of my personality and I use it to improvise through the world,‚Äù says professional bike athlete Brad Simms (@brad_simms).‚Å£
‚Å£
Brad was introduced to BMX at age 11 by his uncle. ‚ÄúSince then I have been privileged enough to ride my bike in 100+ countries, learn multiple languages, broaden my global perspective and make friends all around the world. I could not have done it without the bike.‚Å£
‚Å£
Freedom of expression is my favorite part about riding BMX. The process of connecting dots that never existed is a feeling that never grows old. You are constantly having to reassess your thinking, because of the mental agility it demands.‚Å£
‚Å£
My technique and trick selection are different at this stage of my career. I search for places to do tricks people think are impossible or unique. Jumping over stuff and riding on walls are my favorite things to do now.‚Å£
‚Å£
The streets are the best for my style of riding as I‚Äôm not confined to one course like I might be in competitions. When I pedal around the city, I don‚Äôt know who or what I will run into. The unknown is what keeps me going back day after day. The streets are raw, gritty and unforgiving so you have to always be alert.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Video of @brad_simms by @drewpickles

node.text:
Darci Adele Shepard-Mobbs (@darciadele) and Mia Knights (@miaxalexis) represent the idyllic nature of their long-term relationship through a magical lens inspired by the Renaissance, 19th century English paintings and the folklore of fairies and elves.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúWe like to think the world we have created to be shown by these photos is one of complete content, happiness and calm, since that‚Äôs how we feel around one another,‚Äù explain the 18-year-olds who live in Norfolk, England.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúWe want to convey to people that it‚Äôs OK to wish for things, and that nobody should ever tell you that you can‚Äôt have something. We both used to believe that we would never be able to find the kind of love we now share, and that we weren‚Äôt even allowed to want it.‚Å£
‚Å£
We want to inspire the people that see the fairy tale life we live in to believe that it‚Äôs not just a wish, and that we are real people with insecurities and imperfections who worked as individuals to believe that we are worthy of love, as is everyone in the LGBTQ+ community if they want it.‚Å£
‚Å£
The best thing about being together is the knowledge that whatever we experience as individuals in life, good or bad, exciting or scary, we are going to have a best friend there to experience it at the same time.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo by @darciadele and @miaxalexis
